<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Disk small (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7f</figureCitation>
). Five cylindrical and narrow arms (~2.52 mm) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7f, g</figureCitation>
). Abactinal and actinal surfaces granulose (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7h</figureCitation>
). Skeleton formed by polygonal primary figs (usually hexagonal) that are widely spaced and united by secondary figs of rectangular shape, forming a reticulum. Some carinal and adradial figs with a long, narrow, and blunt spine (~0.77 mm). Papula large and single, found between the abactinal figs. Papulae restricted to abactinal surface. Granules covering body and spines small and with spinous tip. Granules from base of spines larger than at other localities. One conical and elongate subambulacral spine (~0.32 mm), forming a well defined row at base of ambulacral groove (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7i</figureCitation>
). Four slightly flattened adambulacral spines, the median ones being the largest. Eight short and rectangular oral spines, of which the median ones are largest (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Some species of the order Valvatida recorded in northeastern Brazil. Asterinides folium (A-E) A Abactinal view, in detail the superomarginal figs B Actinal view, in detail actinal internidate area C Detail the abactinal intermediate are D Actinal view of the arm E Detail of the mouth; Mithrodia clavigera (F-I) F Abactinal view G Actinal view, in detail the mouth H Abactinal view of the arm, in detail a spine, and I Actinal view of the arm." pageId="10" pageNumber="11">7g</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Colour.</emphasis>
Arms banded with dark brown or red lines, unusually green (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey 1992</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens preserved in alcohol become uniformly white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Mexico, Cuba, Nicaragua, Brazil, Indo-Pacific (except Hawaii) (
<bibRefCitation author="Hayashi, R" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Faculty of Science Hokkaido" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="107 - 204" refId="B54" refString="Hayashi, R, 1940. Contributions to the Classification of the sea-star of Japan. Journal of the Faculty of Science Hokkaido 7: 107 - 204" title="Contributions to the Classification of the sea-star of Japan." volume="7" year="1940">Hayashi 1940</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Abreu-Perez, M" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="29 - 52" refId="B1" refString="Abreu-Perez, M, Solis-Marin, FA, Laguarda-Figueras, A, 2005. Catalogo de los equinodermos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea) neritico-bentonicos del Arquipielago Cubano. Revista de Biologia Tropical 53: 29 - 52" title="Catalogo de los equinodermos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea) neritico-bentonicos del Arquipielago Cubano." volume="53" year="2005">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Abreu-Pérez">Abreu-Perez</normalizedToken>
et al. 2005
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarado, JJ" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="37 - 55" refId="B4" refString="Alvarado, JJ, Solis-Marin, FA, Ahearn, C, 2008. Equinodermos (Echinodermata) del Caribe Centroamericano. Revista de Biologia Tropical 56: 37 - 55" title="Equinodermos (Echinodermata) del Caribe Centroamericano." volume="56" year="2008">Alvarado et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
). In Brazil: ES (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vitória">Vitoria</normalizedToken>
Banks) (
<bibRefCitation author="Brito, IM" journalOrPublisher="Universidade do Brasil, Faculdade Nacional de Filosofia, Centro de Estudos Zoologicos" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 51" refId="B22" refString="Brito, IM, 1968. Asteroides e equinoides do Estado da Guanabara e adjacencias. In: Boletim do Museu Nacional.: 1 - 51" title="Asteroides e equinoides do Estado da Guanabara e adjacencias." volumeTitle="Boletim do Museu Nacional." year="1968">Brito 1968</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey 1992</bibRefCitation>
). In this study we provide the first record for northeastern Brazil. From 24 to 71m in depth (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1816" class="Asteroidea" family="Mithrodiidae" genus="Mithrodia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mithrodia clavigera" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="clavigera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Mithrodia clavigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species of the family 
<taxonomicName class="Asteroidea" family="Mithrodiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Spinulosida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Mithrodiidae</taxonomicName>
recorded for the Western Atlantic. For some time, two species were considered present: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1816" class="Asteroidea" family="Mithrodiidae" genus="Mithrodia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mithrodia clavigera" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="clavigera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Mithrodia clavigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1882" class="Asteroidea" family="Mithrodiidae" genus="Mithrodia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mithrodia victoriae" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="victoriae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Mithrodia victoriae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The later species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bell, FJ" journalOrPublisher="Biological Bulletin" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="121 - 124" refId="B9" refString="Bell, FJ, 1882. Descriptions of new or rare species of Asteroidea in the collection of the British Museum. In: Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, Journal of Zoology.: 121 - 124" title="Descriptions of new or rare species of Asteroidea in the collection of the British Museum." volumeTitle="Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, Journal of Zoology." year="1882">Bell (1882)</bibRefCitation>
, based on two small specimens from submerged banks of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vitória">Vitoria</normalizedToken>
(Victoria Bank) (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Espírito">Espirito</normalizedToken>
Santo, Brazil). Since its description the validity of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1882" class="Asteroidea" family="Mithrodiidae" genus="Mithrodia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mithrodia victoriae" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="victoriae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Mithrodia victoriae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was questioned, and the distinction between these two species was discussed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Engel, H" journalOrPublisher="Zoologische Verhandelingen" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 40" refId="B40" refString="Engel, H, John, DD, Cherbonnier, G, 1948. The genus Mithrodia Gray, 1840. Zoologische Verhandelingen 2: 1 - 40" title="The genus Mithrodia Gray, 1840." volume="2" year="1948">Engel et al. (1948)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Pope, EC" journalOrPublisher="Australian Zoology" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="201 - 216" refId="B121" refString="Pope, EC, Rowe, FWE, 1977. A new genus and two new species in the family Mithrodiidae (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) with comments on the status of species of Mithrodia Gray, 1840. Australian Zoology 19: 201 - 216" title="A new genus and two new species in the family Mithrodiidae (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) with comments on the status of species of Mithrodia Gray, 1840." volume="19" year="1977">Pope and Rowe (1977)</bibRefCitation>
. These authors concluded that the species should be synonymized but, due to the lack of material, this action was not formally carried out. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey (1992)</bibRefCitation>
analised a large number of individuals of several sizes and agreed with the observations of Engel et al. (op. cit.) and Pope and Rowe (op. cit.), considering the two species to be synonyms. The individual we analised is juvenile (R = 9.80 mm) and corresponds to the characterization of juvenile specimens by 
<bibRefCitation author="Engel, H" journalOrPublisher="Zoologische Verhandelingen" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 40" refId="B40" refString="Engel, H, John, DD, Cherbonnier, G, 1948. The genus Mithrodia Gray, 1840. Zoologische Verhandelingen 2: 1 - 40" title="The genus Mithrodia Gray, 1840." volume="2" year="1948">Engel et al. (1948)</bibRefCitation>
. These authors provide details on the aspect of the pedicellariae of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1816" class="Asteroidea" family="Mithrodiidae" genus="Mithrodia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mithrodia clavigera" order="Valvatida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="clavigera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Mithrodia clavigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but pedicellariae were not found in our specimen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="ecological notes">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Ecological notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
This species lives on hard substrates covered by incrusting organisms and in reef gravel (
<bibRefCitation author="Abreu-Perez, M" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="29 - 52" refId="B1" refString="Abreu-Perez, M, Solis-Marin, FA, Laguarda-Figueras, A, 2005. Catalogo de los equinodermos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea) neritico-bentonicos del Arquipielago Cubano. Revista de Biologia Tropical 53: 29 - 52" title="Catalogo de los equinodermos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea) neritico-bentonicos del Arquipielago Cubano." volume="53" year="2005">
